<HEADLINE>
Punishing Half.com/Ebay Deadbeat?
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<POST>
<POSTER> Bil Noe </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2003-07-14T09:19:00 </POSTDATE>
Email: &quot;Bil Noe&quot;&lt;bill ... @hotmail.com&gt;
Groups: misc.consumers


I recently got ripped off by a high-volume half.com/E-Bay seller bearing the
moniker &quot;texasbook&quot;. Apparently, I am not alone; within the past few weeks this
seller has been getting many, many, many negative feedback entries. (the
running totals to date are 887 negative and 537 neutral, as against 3228
positives). Everyone tells the same story: never received the item, the guy
ignores e-mail inquiries. (He seems to still be alive; a small minority do seem
to be getting grudging refunds out of him, and a few are even receiving the
items they paid for.)

The dollar figure in question is only about $13, and I filed a claim with
half.com and will presumably receive a refund, but I'm wondering whether anyone
has ever successfully instigated prosecution of one of these recidivist thieves.
After all, if he has ripped off 800+ people, perhaps to the tune of $10 on
average per person, he has stolen (or attempted to steal, depending on to what
extent half.com keeps reimbursing him) $8000. I don't know how it works down in
Texas, but 'round these parts, if I were to steal $8000, or even attempt to do
so, I'd be looking at a jail sentence.

So what does it take to get the sheriff to show up at this guy's door? It's a
long shot, as I'm not sure E-Bay provides a means to find out his address, but
has anyone tried this? Surely this guy isn't the first crook ever to darken
E-Bay's door.

</POST>



